    \begin{center}
        \LARGE\underline{\textbf{ Photoelectric Effect }}
        
        \vspace{30pt}
        \textbf{Abstract}
        
        \vspace{15pt}
        
        The purpose of the experiment is to verify the particle nature of light and determine the Planck’s constant. In the present experiment, a spectrograph was used to obtain a continuous spectrum from the light source. We then aligned the light of specific frequencies onto a photocell while measuring the current created by the electrons emitted from the cathode. Afterwards, we changed the retarding potential and recorded the corresponding current from a digital multimeter. We calculated the stopping potential for each frequency of light and formed a frequency vs stopping potential graph. Using this graph, we finally found Planck’s constant to be \begin{math} h = 5.36 x 10^{-34} +/- 6.08 x 10^{-34} \emph{Js} \end{math}, which is within \begin{math} 1.27\sigma \end{math} of the true value.
        
        \end{center}
       
        
        \vspace{100pt}
        
       
        \Large{Tunahan Yalçın} %Maybe put this in the middle?
        
