\section{Introduction}
\subsection{History}
    Although the main studies on the photoelectric effect and the quantization of light were conducted in the late 19th and early 20th century, the foundation of the photoelectric effect dates back to mid-19th century. The first known study was conducted by Alexandre Edmond Becquerel in 1839 while studying the effect of light on electrolytic cells, which led to the discovery of the photovoltaic effect. Even though his discovery was not equivalent to the photoelectric effect, his work showed a strong relationship between light and electronic properties of materials. After the Becquerel’ discovery, the main focus was on the practical applications of the photoelectric without understanding the fundamentals of it until 1887. \par
	In 1887, Franck Hertz was studying on the photoelectric effect where he observed the production and reception of electromagnetic waves. In his studies, he used a coil with a spark gap where a spark would be observed upon detection of electromagnetic waves. In the light of his work, studies on the photoelectric and its properties increased dramatically. It was studied by many known scientists like J.J. Thomson, Max Planck until the explanation came from Albert Einstein in 1905.\par
	After the groundbreaking theory of Einsten in his article "On a Heuristic Viewpoint Concerning the Production and Transformation of Light", many scientist focused on the proving the theory. Regarding the issue, in 1914, Robert Andrews Millikan showed Einstein’s prediction to be true by observing that the energy of the photoelectrons increase with increasing frequency and it is independent of the light intensity. This observation lead to Einstein winning a nobel prize for his works on the matter.



\subsection{Theory}

    The photoelectric effect is described as the emission of electrons from a material surface or within the material itself while illuminated by light. There has been many explanations to address the issue. First, Max Planck suggested that the light waves consist of small packets of energy, which is now called photons, which eliminate the problem of Ultra-Violet Catastrophe. Following his proposition, Einstein using the concept of quantized light and he proposed that the energy of each quantum of light carries an energy, E, accordingly with \emph{E = hf}. This assumption led him to predict the maximum energy of electrons to be
    
    \begin{equation}\label{1}
        K_{max} = hf - \phi
    \end{equation}
    
    where \begin{math} \phi \end{math} is the work function of the metal used to observe the photoelectric effect. In this formula, work function is a characteristic property of the metal which can be described as the minimum energy that a metal requires to emit an electron from its surface.. \par
    
    \begin{math} K_{max} \end{math} can be found by applying an inverse potential to the electrons, namely the stopping voltage \begin{math} V_{s} \end{math} where the current diminishes
    
    \begin{equation}\label{2}
        K_{max} = qV_{s}
    \end{equation}
    
    Putting this into \eqref{1} , we find that 
    
    \begin{equation}\label{3}
        hf = qV_{s} + \phi
    \end{equation}
    
