    \vspace{20pt}
    
\subsection{How the setup works} %Find a better title!

Mercury lamp in the photo emits light through its front hole, then the light is focused with the help of the lenses which later is reflected from the mirror (see Figure 2). The process of focusing is to decrease spreading out and avoiding striking to the anode. The reflected light then goes through the spectrograph which is used to align the desired color onto the cathode.\par
	
The photons strike the cathode and cause metal to emit electrons if the incoming photon energy is sufficient, i.e., it is higher than the work function of the metal. The emitting of the electrons produce a current which can be amplified by the current amplifier in the circuit. Current can be adjusted by changing the potential on the anode with the moving coil voltmeter. Due to the potential on the anode, emitted electrons lose energy and some fail to reach the anode which results in a decrease in the current

    
\newpage

\subsection{Procedure}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The power supplies are off and the voltage settings are at 0 before proceeding with the experiment
    \item Before turning the power on, close the casing of the setup and turn off the lights since it may damage the photocell and may cause false negative results by reversing the current on the anode
    \item The mercury lamp was connected to the power source and heated up.
    \item The orientation of the grating was adjusted as the yellow light strikes the photocell
    \item The current for 0V was noted and the voltage was increased by approximately 0.05V.
    \item . The current was noted with each voltage, until current reaches 0. After reaching 0, other measurements were also noted as increasing the voltage (doğru mu?).
    \item The steps 5-7 was repeated for green, turquoise, blue and violet.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Analysis and Calculations}
Calculation of the errors in current and voltage were completed with the code (see Appendix). In the following section, the raw data (see appendix) was put into graphs and two line fits were made. In the graphs, each parameter could not be given but the code we used to draw the graphs are included in the appendix as well. Importantly, to clarify the errors, the current errors has been multiplied with 10.

\begin{equation}
    a_{1}V + b_{1} = I 
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
    a_{2}V + b_{2} = I 
\end{equation}

Also please note that the errors in current were multiplied with 10 in order to show the errors with better clarity

