To find \begin{math} V_{s} \end{math}, we can use our fit values of \begin{math} a_{1}, a_{2}, b_{1}, b_{2} \end{math} and find their intersections V = \begin{math} V_{s} \end{math} by using the following formula

\begin{equation}\label{6}
    V_{s}a_{1} + b_{1} = V_{s}a_{2} + b_{2}
\end{equation}


and we found \begin{math} \Delta V_{s} \end{math} by using error propagation which is given by

\begin{equation}\label{7}
    \Delta f(x_{i}) = \sqrt{\sum(\frac{\partial f}{\partial x_{i}}\Delta x_{i})^2}
\end{equation}

Equations \eqref{6} and \eqref{7} give us 

\vspace{10pt}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ |c|c|c| } 
 \hline
 Color & \begin{math} V_{s} \end{math} & \begin{math} \Delta V_{s} \end{math} \\ \hline
 Yellow & 0.414 V & 0.880 \\ \hline
 Green & 0.400 V & 0.568 \\ \hline
 Turquoise & 0.573 V & 0.562 \\ \hline
 Blue & 0.670 V & 0.678 \\ \hline
 Violet & 1.217 V & 0.700 \\ \hline
 \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\vspace{20pt}

In the experiment, the frequencies of colors were given to us as certain values which are

\begin{center}
    \begin{tabular}{|c|c|}
     \hline
      Color  & Frequency (\begin{math} e14 \end{math} Hz)\\ \hline \hline
      Yellow   & 5.19 \\ \hline
      Green   & 5.49 \\ \hline
      Turquoise   & 6.08 \\ \hline
      Blue   & 6.88 \\ \hline
      Violet   & 7.41 \\ \hline
    \end{tabular}
\end{center}

\newpage

 \begin{math} V_{s} \end{math} and f were put in a graph with error bars and fitted a line.
 
 \begin{center}
     \begingroup
    \setlength{\intextsep}{5pt}
    \setlength{\columnsep}{20pt}
    \begin{wrapfigure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=11cm]{fvsv2.png}
    \newline
    \caption{Figure 8: frequency f vs stopping potential \begin{math} V_{s} \end{math} }\label{fig:fig8}
    \end{wrapfigure}

      \endgroup
 \end{center}
 
 \vspace{20pt}
 
 The fit has the formula
 \begin{center}
     \begin{math} V_{s} \end{math} = p1.f + p0
 \end{center}
 where p1 is \begin{math} \frac{h}{q} \end{math} and p0 is \begin{math} \frac{-\phi}{q} \end{math},
 q= \begin{math} 1.60*10^{-19} \end{math} \emph{coulomb}. Using these we get \newline
 
 \vspace{5pt}
 
 \begin{math}
\frac{h}{q} = 3.35 x 10^{-15} +/- 3.80^{-15} \frac{\emph{Js}}{\emph{coulomb}} 
\newline

\vspace{5pt}

\Rightarrow h = 5.36 x 10^{-34} +/- 6.08 x 10^{-34} \emph{Js} 
\newline

\end{math}

\begin{math}
 \frac{-\phi}{q} = -1.44 +/- 2.38
 
 \vspace{5pt}
 
\Rightarrow \phi = 0.230 +/- 0.380 \frac{\emph{J}}{\emph{coulomb}}
 
\end{math}
 
\newpage

\section{Conclusion}
The purpose of the experiment was to verify the quantum nature of light and to get the Planck's constant using the phenomenon of the Photoelectric effect. The data showed linear relationship between current and reverse voltage as discussed and shown in section 3.In addition, the data frequency of light vs stopping voltage also showed linear relationship. These results agree with Einstein's proposition. We calculated the Planck's constant to be 
\begin{center}
    \begin{math} h = 5.36 x 10^{-34} +/- 6.08 x 10^{-34} \emph{Js} \end{math}
\end{center}
Comparing this result with the known value for the Planck's constant,
\begin{center}
    \begin{math} h_{true} = 6.62 x 10^{-34} \emph{Js} 
        \end{math}
\end{center}


\vspace{2pt}

\begin{center}
    \begin{math}
     \huge\frac{|h_{true}-h|}{\Delta h} = \frac{6.63 - 5.36}{6.08} = 1.27
    \end{math}
\end{center}

\vspace{2pt}

\begin{center}
    \begin{math}
     \huge\frac{\Delta h}{h} = 113 \%
    \end{math}
\end{center}

It can be concluded that this is a bad result since it contains a big uncertainty, despite the fact the known value is within \begin{math} 1.27\sigma, \end{math} \begin{math} \Delta h \end{math} is \begin{math} 113\% \end{math} of \emph{h}. The result can be improved by studying the following possible causes of error

\begin{itemize}
    \item Frequencies of light are taken to be absolute whereas the colors in the spectrum are not separated enough due to the small distance between target and spectrograph.
    \item The frequencies of the colors used were not measured, but chosen with eye, hence there was no way of knowing the actual frequencies.
    \item The target is rather sensitive to light but regardless one has to expose the target to unwanted light every time whilst changing the color. The target should be isolated from the environment more precisely.
\end{itemize}


